This project uses canary ("honeypot") files to catch automated / un-triaged vulnerability reports.

## Canary files

The following files in this repository are **canaries**, a form of **honeypot**. They are not production code. They are never imported, never executed, and not included in release artefacts:

- `[your-canary-paths-here]`

Each canary file contains a unique identifier. If you use one UUID per language (recommended), list them all: `[your-rotated-uuid-1]`, `[your-rotated-uuid-2]`, ….

Canaries may also be embedded in actual project code without warning.

## Triage rule

Any vulnerability report that meets **any** of the following criteria will be **closed without review**:

1. References any canary UUID (`[your-rotated-uuid]` or any variant).
2. Cites a file path at a canary location in this repository.
3. References a function name that exists only in a canary file.
4. Claims a vulnerability in a canary hidden inside real code.
5. References a function name or file name that does not exist in this repository.

If you believe your report is being mis-categorised by this policy, please reply to the closure with a working proof-of-concept — a crash log from a sanitizer build, a reproducer script producing unauthorised capability, or similar concrete evidence. Reports claiming "this looks exploitable" are not valid.

## What we consider a valid report

- The claimed vulnerability exists in code that runs in a real execution path.
- The function, file, and line numbers cited exist in the current tree.
- A proof-of-concept is included or can be produced on request.
- The finding is not already addressed upstream or by documented platform-level mitigations.

## Background

This triage policy is a response to a documented pattern of AI-generated / un-triaged vulnerability reports against open-source projects. See:

- [curl's policy notes](https://daniel.haxx.se/blog/2024/01/02/the-i-in-llm-stands-for-intelligence/)
- [Django's 2026-02-04 post](https://www.djangoproject.com/weblog/2026/feb/04/)
- [Seth Larson on urllib3](https://sethmlarson.dev/slop-security-reports)

The canaries and this rule reduce maintainer triage load without penalising good-faith reporters who read repository context before filing.
